attributes.name: Eat more plant-based foods rich in vitamin D
attributes.description: Plant-based foods rich in vitamin D include some mushrooms and fortified foods like some breakfast cereals and milk alternatives. Try to opt for wholegrain cereals like bran flakes and unsweetened milk alternatives. If you follow a vegetarian diet, vitamin D is also found in eggs and yoghurt.

attributes.description: You might benefit from a vitamin D supplement containing 400-1000 IU (10-25 mcg) per day. A vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) supplement is the best form to take as your body finds it easiest to absorb and use. Avoid taking more than 4000 IU (100 mcg) per day.

attributes.name: Take a plant-based omega-3 supplement
attributes.description: Algae-based omega-3 supplements are a good vegan source of both EPA and DHA (important types of omega-3). Avoid taking more than 3 g a day. If you experience any mild side effects, like heartburn, burping, bloating, or diarrhoea, starting with a lower dose and increasing it gradually can help. If you have a bleeding disorder or take blood-thinning medication, like warfarin, talk to your doctor before taking an omega-3 supplement.

attributes.name: Omega-3 & 6
attributes.description: Omega-3 and omega-6 fatty acids are types of fat that you can only get from your diet. Both omega-3 and omega-6 are essential for your health, but it's important to get the balance right ‚Äî that's why we measure your omega-6:omega-3 (AA:EPA) ratio. Ideally, this ratio should be 2:1, but most Western diets lead to ratios around 10:1. This can cause chronic inflammation and increase your risk of heart disease, arthritis, diabetes, and some cancers.

attributes.name: Advanced iron profile
attributes.description: Your body uses iron to make haemoglobin ‚Äî a part of red blood cells that carries oxygen around your body. If you don't get enough iron you might develop iron deficiency anaemia. Tiredness, shortness of breath and heart palpitations are signs you might be deficient. A full iron profile measures 5 iron markers: ferritin, total iron binding capacity (TIBC), transferrin saturation (FESA), total iron and unsaturated iron binding capacity (UIBC).

attributes.name: Thyroid profile
attributes.description: The thyroid is a gland in your neck. It produces hormones that control your body's growth and metabolism. An overactive or underactive thyroid causes hormonal imbalances that can cause symptoms like weight gain or loss, tiredness, low mood, anxiety, depression and difficulty sleeping. A basic thyroid profile measures Thyroxine (T4), the main hormone produced by your thyroid, and Thyroid Stimulating Hormone (TSH), a hormone that regulates your thyroid.

attributes.name: CRP
attributes.description: A high sensitivity C-reactive protein (hs-CRP) test can tell you if you're suffering from chronic inflammation ‚Äî a strong risk factor for heart disease. A raised CRP level is also linked to a number of other health problems, like diabetes, obesity, high blood pressure, and some cancers.

attributes.name: Vitamin B9 & B12 (Active)
attributes.description: Vitamin B12 plays a key role in the normal functioning of the nervous system. It also works closely with vitamin B9 (folate) to make red blood cells. A deficiency of either can cause tiredness, pins and needles, heart palpitations, shortness of breath and muscle weakness.

attributes.name: Vitamin D
attributes.description: Vitamin D helps your body absorb calcium and helps with maintaing healthy skin and bones. It also plays an important role in your immune system. Vitamin D deficiency is linked to fatigue, bone and muscle pain, as well as getting ill more often than usual.

attributes.body: This is in range which is great but slightly below optimal. You could add a daily vitamin D supplement as per NHE advice to get this into the optimal range.

Your Hs-CRP levels continue to be less than 1mg/L. This means that there is little evidence of inflammation in the body, and is related to reduced risk of developing heart disease. It is important to remember that cardiovascular risk is best interpreted alongside other risk factors such as smoking, family history and tests including lipid profile.

Your omega-6 (AA) level is too high compared to your omega-3 (EPA) level. This is linked with an increased risk of developing heart disease. This can happen if you're eating a standard western diet. You can improve your ratio by increasing your intake of omega-3s and reducing your intake of omega-6 fats. Please see the recommendations in your health plan.

Your omega-3 index is in the intermediate range. A level of more than 8% is associated with a lower risk of death from coronary heart disease. To improve your omega-3 index so it's in target range, it's recommended that you increase your intake of omega-3 fats (EPA and DHA) by 0.5-1.0 grams per day. You might get enough from eating more oily fish, but fish oil supplements are likely to be necessary. There are also vegan omega-3 supplements, like algal oil. Please see the recommendations in your health plan.

attributes.name: Vitamin D
attributes.description: Supports your bone, muscle, and immune health.

content.text: Vitamin D is essential for healthy bones, teeth, and muscles. It also supports your immune system ‚Äî helping you fight off infections.

product_did_you_know_content.text: Vitamin D acts on areas of your brain linked to mental health. Maintaining your levels above 50 nmol/L might help lower your risk of low mood, anxiety, and depression.

content.text: Our vegan vitamin D supplement is made from the plant material lichen and only uses high quality, ethical-sourced ingredients. It‚Äôs additive-free and in the form of vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) ‚Äî the form your body finds easiest to absorb and use.
All of our supplements are made locally in the UK.
Dosage
1 capsule provides 1000 IU (25 mcg).
Recommended intakes
25-50 nmol/L: Consider 4000 IU (100 mcg) a day for 10 weeks or an ongoing dose of 1000 IU (25 mcg) ‚Äî1-4 Thriva capsules a day.
50-75 nmol/L: Consider 1000 IU (25 mcg) to increase to an optimal level ‚Äî 1 Thriva capsule a day.
50-75 nmol/L with Crohn's or coeliac disease: Consider 4000 IU (100 mcg) a day to prevent a deficiency ‚Äî 4 Thriva capsules a day.
75-120 nmol/L: Consider 10 mcg a day (400 IU) from October-March or if you have little sunshine exposure*
Take capsules with a meal.

*Public Health England (PHE) advises that everyone should consider taking a daily vitamin D supplement from October to March. This is because sunlight exposure is low and your body gets most of its vitamin D this way.

attributes.name: Omega-3
attributes.sub_title: Vegan source of EPA and DHA
attributes.description: Supports your brain, eye, and heart health.

content.text: Omega-3 fatty acids are a type of essential unsaturated fat that are important for your brain health and vision. Omega-3s can also help maintain healthy cholesterol levels ‚Äî linking them to better heart health.

product_did_you_know_content.text: A diet high in omega-3s is linked to longer, better quality sleep. Likely because it helps you produce the sleep hormone melatonin.

content.text: Our vegan omega-3 supplement is made from a type of algae (Schizochytrium sp.) and only uses high quality, ethically-sourced ingredients. It‚Äôs also additive-free and made locally in the UK.¬†

Our omega-3 supplement is a great source of both EPA and DHA ‚Äî forms of omega-3 your body find easy to use. Interestingly, the reason fish are such a great source of omega-3 is because they eat algae. By choosing an algae-based omega-3 supplement, you‚Äôre going straight to the source. This means it‚Äôs more sustainable than farmed fish oil. It‚Äôs also why an algae-based supplement costs slightly more.
Dosage: 2 softgels, taken daily with a meal.

As omega-3s are a type of unsaturated fat, they can expire quicker than other supplements. This is partly why we sell our omega-3 in smaller quantities than our other supplements. It also makes the cost more manageable ‚Äî algal oil is in high demand making it more expensive to source.¬†
There are no established UK guidelines on how much omega-3s you need in your diet. Most organisations suggest a minimum of 250-500 mg combined EPA and DHA each day for adults.

attributes.name: Omega-3 Index
attributes.description: An omega-3 index measures the amount of omega-3 fatty acids in your red blood cells. This test helps determine your risk of heart disease.

attributes.name: Omega-6:omega-3 (AA:EPA) ratio
attributes.description: Omega-3 and omega-6 fatty acids are essential for your health, but it's important to get the balance right. Ideally, your omega-6:omega-3 ratio should be 2:1. Most Western diets tend to be around 10:1 ‚Äî which is linked with an increased risk of heart disease, diabetes, and arthritis. This test measures a specific type of omega-6:3 ratio, your AA:EPA ratio.

attributes.name: Total iron-binding capacity (TIBC)
attributes.description: A total iron-binding capacity (TIBC) test measures your blood's capacity to bind and transport iron. It can help check for iron deficiency or iron overload.

attributes.name: Unsaturated iron binding capacity (UIBC)
attributes.description: An unsaturated iron-binding capacity (UIBC) test measures the amount of transferrin (transfers iron around your body) that's not bound to iron. This helps check for iron deficiency or iron overload.

attributes.name: Ferritin
attributes.description: A ferritin test measures the amount of iron stored in your body. It can help check for iron deficiency or iron overload. Iron is essential for helping carry oxygen around your body.

attributes.name: Iron
attributes.description: Iron is an important part of hemoglobin, which carries oxygen around your body. Low iron levels can cause fatigue, shortness of breath, anxiety, and head pain.

attributes.name: Transferrin saturation
attributes.description: Transferrin is a protein that transports iron around the body. A transferrin saturation test measures the amount of iron bound to transferrin. This helps check for iron deficiency or iron overload.

attributes.name: Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)
attributes.description: Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) is a hormone that regulates the release of hormones from your thyroid. These hormones, T3 and T4, help control growth and metabolism. A TSH test can check for hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism.

attributes.name: Free thyroxine (FT4)
attributes.description: Thyroxine (T4) is the main hormone produced by your thyroid. It plays an essential role in regulating the energy your body uses. Free T4 measures the amount of T4 that's available for your body to use. This test can help check for hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism.

attributes.name: CRP (high sensitivity)
attributes.description: High-sensitivity C-reactive protein (hs-CRP) measures low levels of inflammation ‚Äî a risk factor for heart disease. hs-CRP is also linked to a number of other health problems including diabetes, obesity, high blood pressure, and certain cancers.

attributes.name: Active B12
attributes.description: Vitamin B12 is essential for a healthy nervous system. An active B12 test measures the amount of B12 that available for your body to use. If you‚Äôre deficient it can cause tiredness, pins and needles, heart palpitations, shortness of breath, and muscle weakness.

attributes.name: Folate
attributes.description: Folate (vitamin B9) is needed for a healthy liver, skin, hair, and eyes. If you‚Äôre deficient it can cause tiredness, pins and needles, heart palpitations, shortness of breath, and muscle weakness.

attributes.name: Vitamin D
attributes.description: Vitamin D helps your body absorb calcium. It's needed to maintain strong bones and a healthy immune system. If you don't get enough you might feel tired, get sick often, have weak bones, and feel anxious or depressed.
